9\n|percentage=18.3\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Communist Party of Great Britain\n|candidate=[[Bob Stewart (communist)|Bob Stewart]]\n|votes=10,264\n|percentage=5.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=19,475\n|percentage=11.0\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=15,983\n|percentage=9.1\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes=\n|percentage=84.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner=Liberal Party (UK)\n|loser=Labour Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner=Unionist Party (Scotland)\n|loser=Scottish Prohibition Party\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=[[1935 United Kingdom general election|General election 1935]]: Dundee (2 seats) <ref>Whitaker's Almanack, 1939</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Unionist Party (Scotland)\n|candidate=[[Florence Horsbrugh, Baroness Horsbrugh|Florence Horsbrugh]]\n|votes=50,542\n|percentage=26.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Dingle Foot]]\n|votes=49,632\n|percentage=26.4\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Michael Marcus (politician)|Michael Marcus]]\n|votes=44,457\n|percentage=23.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Robert Gibson, Lord Gibson|Robert Gibson]]\n|votes=43,747\n|percentage=23.2\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=6,085\n|percentage=3.2\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=5,175\n|percentage=2.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes=\n|percentage=84.7\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner=Unionist Party (Scotland)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner=Liberal Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Elections in the 1940s===\n[[File:John Strachey by Lady Ottoline Morrell.jpg|thumb|120px|Strachey]]\n{{Election box begin|title=[[1945 United Kingdom general election|General election 1945]]: Dundee (2 seats)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Thomas Cook (Scottish politician)|Thomas Cook]]\n|votes=48,804\n|percentage=28.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[John Strachey (politician)|John Strachey]]\n|votes=48,393\n|percentage=28.4\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Dingle Foot]]\n|votes=33,230\n|percentage=19.5\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Unionist Party (Scotland)\n|candidate=[[Florence Horsbrugh, Baroness Horsbrugh|Florence Horsbrugh]]\n|votes=32,309\n|percentage=18.9\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Scottish National Party\n|candidate=[[Arthur Donaldson]]\n|votes=7,775\n|percentage=4.56\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=15,163\n|percentage=8.9\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes=\n|percentage=79.2\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner=Labour Party (UK)\n|loser=Liberal Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner=Labour Party (UK)\n|loser=Unionist Party (Scotland)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*[[F. W. S. Craig]], ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1832 - 1885''\n*[[F. W. S. Craig]], ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918 - 1949''\n*Debrett's House of Commons and the Judicial Bench 1889\n*{{Rayment-hc|d|4|date=March 2012}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Scottish Westminster constituencies}}\n\n[[Category:Historic parliamentary constituencies in Scotland (Westminster)]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1832]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies disestablished in 1950]]\n[[Category:Politics of Dundee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Dundee\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = \n |map2        = \n |map_entity  = \n |map_year    = \n |year        = 1832\n |abolished   = 1950\n |type        = Burgh\n |elects_howmany = 1832\u20131868: One<br />1868\u20131950: Two \n |previous    = \n |next        = [[Dundee East (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee East]]<br /> [[Dundee West (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee West]]\n |region      = Scotland\n |county      = \n |towns       = [[Dundee]]\n}}\n\n'''Dundee''' was a [[constituency]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] from [[1832 United Kingdom general election|1832]] to [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]], when it was split into [[Dundee East (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee East]] and [[Dundee West (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee West]].\n\nFrom 1832 to [[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868]] it elected one [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) using the [[first-past-the-post]] voting system, and from 1868 until its abolition for the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 general election]] it elected two MPs using the [[Plurality-at-large voting|bloc vote]] system.\n\n== Politics and history of the constituency ==\n\n[[Winston Churchill]] became Member of Parliament for Dundee in a by-election of 1908 soon after losing his [[Manchester North West (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester North West]] seat and retained the seat until 1922.\n\nIn 1906, the explorer [[Ernest Shackleton]] unsuccessfully ran as a candidate for the [[Liberal Unionist Party]].<ref>{{cite book \n  | last = Morrell\n  | first = Margot\n  |author2=Stephanie Capparell\n  | title = Shackleton's Way\n  | publisher = Nicholas Brealey\n  | date = 2003\n  | isbn = 1-85788-318-7\n  | page = 32 }}</ref>\n\nFrom its creation in 1832 the seat did not return a [[Conservative Party(UK)|Conservative]] member until 1931 when [[Florence Horsbrugh, Baroness Horsbrugh|Florence Horsbrugh]] was elected.<ref name=Baxter>{{cite journal|last1=Baxter|first1=Kenneth|title=Florence Gertrude Horsbrugh The Conservative Party's forgotten first lady|journal=Conservative History Journal|date=2009|issue=8|page=21|url=https://conservativehistory.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/chj-winter-2009-10.pdf|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> Originally a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] stronghold, the seat was one of the first in Scotland to return a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate, [[Alexander Wilkie]], who was elected in 1906.<ref name=\"Red Scotland blog\">{{cite web|title=Tracing the development of Red Scotland|url=http://archives-records-artefacts.blogspot.co.uk/2010/10/tracing-development-of-red-scotland.html|publisher=Archives, Records and Artefacts at the University of Dundee|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] both Churchill, still then a Liberal, and Wilkie were supported by the local [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionists]], as well as their own party organisations.<ref name=\"KenefickBaxter\">{{cite book|title=Jute No More|year=2011|publisher=Dundee University Press|location=Dundee|isbn=978-1-84586-090-5|page=205|author=Baxter, Kenneth|author2=Kenefick William|editor=Jim Tomlinson and Christopher A. Whatley|chapter=Labour Politics and the Dundee Working Class c 1895-1936}}</ref> From 1923 onwards the Conservatives/Unionists and Liberals each ran only one candidate in the constituancy. This was part of an unofficial agreement between the two parties at a local level, with the understanding being that their supporters would give their other vote to the other party's candidate.<ref name=Baxter2>{{cite journal|last1=Baxter|first1=Kenneth|title=Florence Gertrude Horsbrugh The Conservative Party's forgotten first lady|journal=Conservative History Journal|date=2009|issue=8|pages=21\u201322|url=https://conservativehistory.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/chj-winter-2009-10.pdf|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Boundaries==\n\nThe boundaries of the constituency, as set out in the [[Representation of the People (Scotland) Act 1832]], were-\n\n:\"From the Point, on the East of the Town, at which the Shore of the Firth of Tay would be cut by a straight Line to be drawn from the Tower (in Fife) of Mr. Dalgleish of Scotscraig to the Point at which the Stobsmuir Road is joined by the old Road by Stobsmuir and Clepington and the old Craigie Road, in a straight Line to the said Point at which the Stobsmuir Road is joined by the old Road by Stobsmuir and Clepington and the old Craigie Road; thence, Westward, along the old Road by Stobsmuir and Clepington to the Point called Kings Cross, at which the several Boundaries of the Parishes of Dundee, Strathmartin, and Liff meet; thence in a straight Line to a Point on the Liff Road which is distant Twelve hundred Yards (measured along the Liff Road) to the West of the Point at which the Newtyle Road leaves the same; thence in a straight Line drawn due South to the Shore of the Firth of Tay; thence along the Shore of the Firth of Tay to the Point first described.\"<ref>Representation of the People (Scotland) Act 1832, Schedule (M).</ref>\n\n== Members of Parliament ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Member\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Member\n|-\n|[[1832 United Kingdom general election|1832]]\n{{Party name with colour|Whig (British political party)}}<ref name=\"stookssmith1842\">{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Henry Stooks|title=The Register of Parliamentary Contested Elections|date=1842|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall & Company|pages=199\u2013200|edition=Second|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VQgHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA199|accessdate=2 September 2018 |via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n|[[George Kinloch (MP)|George Kinloch]]\n|rowspan=\"5\" colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"| 1 seat<br />until 1868\n|-\n|[[1833 Dundee by-election|1833 by-election]]\n{{Party name with colour|Whig (British political party)}}<ref name=\"stookssmith1842\"/><ref>{{cite book|first1=Edward|last1=Churton|author-link1=Edward Churton|title=The Assembled Commons or Parliamentary Biographer: 1838|date=1838|page=176|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FVwEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA176 |via=[[Google Books]] |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Henry Parnell, 1st Baron Congleton|Sir Henry Parnell]]\n|-\n|[[1841 United Kingdom general election|1841]]\n{{Party name with colour|Whig (British political party)}}<ref name=\"stookssmith1842\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=General Election |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18410705/003/0002 |accessdate=2 September 2018 |work=Morning Post |date=5 July 1841 |page=2 |via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n|[[George Duncan (politician)|George Duncan]]\n|-\n|[[1857 United Kingdom general election|1857]]\n| bgcolor={{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}} |\n| [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=McIntosh |first1=Iain D. |title=Sir John Ogilvy, 9th Baronet of Inverquharity |url=http://www.pglforfarshire.org/Sir_John_Ogilvy.html |website=Provincial Grand Lodge of Forfarshire |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hawkins |first1=Angus |title=Victorian Political Culture: 'Habits of Heart & Mind' |date=2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-872848-1 |page=202 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-PcJCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202 |lccn=2014951692 |accessdate=2 September 2018 |via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Sir John Ogilvy, 9th Baronet|Sir John Ogilvy]]\n|-\n|[[1859 United Kingdom general election|1859]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" bgcolor={{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}} |\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Liberal Party (UK)|{{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/shortname}}]]\n|-\n|[[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868]]\n{{Party name with c