{"title_page": "Satellite internet constellation", "text_new": "{{Short description|Computer network architecture based on orbital satellites}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2018}}\nA '''satellite internet constellation'''\u2014sometimes referred to as a '''megaconstellation'''<ref name=sn20190625>\n{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/megaconstellation-ventures-cautious-about-deployment-milestones/ |title=Megaconstellation ventures cautious about deployment milestones |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=25 June 2019 |accessdate=3 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\u2014is a large [[Satellite constellation|constellation]] of artificial satellites orbiting in [[low-Earth orbit]] (LEO), working together to provide [[high-throughput satellite]] (HTS) communication to facilitate [[Latency (engineering)|low-latency]] [[broadband]] internet service to various business and individual nodes on the surface of Earth.<ref name=satnews20180308/>\n\nMore than 18,000 new satellites have been proposed to be launched and placed in LEO orbits between 2019 and 2025.<ref name=satnews20180308>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.satnews.com/story.php?number=257303683 |title=NSR Reports China's Ambitious Constellation of 300 Small Satellites in LEO |work=SatNews |date=8 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |quote=The most visible or at least, the most talked about LEO contenders stem from the U.S. and Canada, numbering at least 11 with planned satellites to be deployed at around 18,000. }}</ref>  This is more than ten times as many satellites as the sum of all active satellites in space as of March 2018.\n\nWhile more-limited [[Satellite Internet access|satellite internet]] services have been available through [[geosynchronous orbit|geosynchronous]] [[commsat]]s orbiting in the [[Clarke Belt]] for years, these have been of quite limited [[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] (not broadband), high-[[Latency (engineering)|latency]], and provided at such a relatively high [[price]] that [[demand]] for the services offered has been quite low.<ref name=ars20130215>\n{{cite news |last=Brodkin|first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2013/02/satellite-internet-faster-than-advertised-but-latency-still-awful/#p3n |title=Satellite Internet faster than advertised, but latency still awful |work=Ars Technica |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |quote=''Satellite latency is 638ms, 20 times higher than terrestrial broadband.'' }}</ref><ref name=vsat2013>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.vsat-systems.com/satellite-internet-explained/latency.html |title=Latency- why is it a big deal for Satellite Internet? |year=2013 |publisher=VSAT Systems |accessdate=24 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=nia2014>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.niasat.com/q-what-is-the-difference-between-terrestrial-land-based-internet-and-satellite-internet-service/ |title=What is the difference between terrestrial (land based) Internet and satellite Internet service? |work=Network Innovation Associates |year=2014 |accessdate=24 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nSatellite internet constellations have been proposed and under [[new product development|development]] since 2014.  Internet sat constellations are planned by \n[[OneWeb]] ([[OneWeb satellite constellation|OneWeb constellation]]),<ref name=srb20140603>\n{{cite news |last1=Boucher|first1=Marc |title=Will Google Build a Satellite Constellation? |url=http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html |accessdate=25 March 2018 |publisher=SpaceRef Business |date=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj20141107>\n{{cite news |last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe |last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy |title=Elon Musk\u2019s Next Mission: Internet Satellites  SpaceX, Tesla Founder Explores Venture to Make Lighter, Cheaper Satellites |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062 |accessdate=25 March 2018 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=11 July 2014}}</ref> \n[[SpaceX]] ([[Starlink]]),<ref name=lat20150116>\n{{cite news |last1=Petersen|first1=Melody |title=Elon Musk and Richard Branson invest in satellite-Internet ventures |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html |accessdate=19 January 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=16 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=ars20171004>\n{{cite news |last=Brodkin|first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/ |title=SpaceX and OneWeb broadband satellites raise fears about space debris |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=2017-10-04 |accessdate=2017-10-07 }}</ref> \n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] ([[Project Kuiper]]),<ref name=cnbc20190404>{{cite news |last=Sheetz|first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |title=Amazon wants to launch thousands of satellites so it can offer broadband internet from space |work=[[CNBC]] |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=19 September 2019 }}</ref><ref name=sn20190708>[https://spacenews.com/amazon-lays-out-constellation-service-goals-deployment-and-deorbit-plans-to-fcc/ Amazon lays out constellation service goals, deployment and deorbit plans to FCC], Caleb Henry, [[SpaceNews]], 8 July 2019, accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> \n[[Samsung]], [[Boeing]], and China (Hongwan),<ref name=satnews20180308/> among others.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Communications satellite constellations|*]]\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access|constellation]]\n[[Category:Spaceflight]]\n\n{{space-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Computer network architecture based on orbital satellites}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2018}}\nA '''satellite internet constellation'''\u2014sometimes referred to as a '''megaconstellation'''<ref name=sn20190625>\n{{cite news |last=Henry|first=Caleb |url=https://spacenews.com/megaconstellation-ventures-cautious-about-deployment-milestones/ |title=Megaconstellation ventures cautious about deployment milestones |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=25 June 2019 |accessdate=3 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\u2014is a large [[Satellite constellation|constellation]] of artificial satellites orbiting in [[low-Earth orbit]] (LEO), working together to provide [[high-throughput satellite]] (HTS) communication to facilitate [[Latency (engineering)|low-latency]] [[broadband]] internet service to various business and individual nodes on the surface of Earth.<ref name=satnews20180308/>\n\nMore than 18,000 new satellites have been proposed to be launched and placed in LEO orbits between 2019 and 2025.<ref name=satnews20180308>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.satnews.com/story.php?number=257303683 |title=NSR Reports China's Ambitious Constellation of 300 Small Satellites in LEO |work=SatNews |date=8 March 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |quote=The most visible or at least, the most talked about LEO contenders stem from the U.S. and Canada, numbering at least 11 with planned satellites to be deployed at around 18,000. }}</ref>  This is more than ten times as many satellites as the sum of all active satellites in space as of March 2018.\n\nWhile more-limited [[Satellite Internet access|satellite internet]] services have been available through [[geosynchronous orbit|geosynchronous]] [[commsat]]s orbiting in the [[Clarke Belt]] for years, these have been of quite limited [[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] (not broadband), high-[[Latency (engineering)|latency]], and provided at such a relatively high [[price]] that [[demand]] for the services offered has been quite low.<ref name=ars20130215>\n{{cite news |last=Brodkin|first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2013/02/satellite-internet-faster-than-advertised-but-latency-still-awful/#p3n |title=Satellite Internet faster than advertised, but latency still awful |work=Ars Technica |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |quote=''Satellite latency is 638ms, 20 times higher than terrestrial broadband.'' }}</ref><ref name=vsat2013>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.vsat-systems.com/satellite-internet-explained/latency.html |title=Latency- why is it a big deal for Satellite Internet? |year=2013 |publisher=VSAT Systems |accessdate=24 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=nia2014>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.niasat.com/q-what-is-the-difference-between-terrestrial-land-based-internet-and-satellite-internet-service/ |title=What is the difference between terrestrial (land based) Internet and satellite Internet service? |work=Network Innovation Associates |year=2014 |accessdate=24 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nSatellite internet constellations have been proposed and under [[new product development|development]] since 2014.  Internet sat constellations are planned by \n[[OneWeb]] ([[OneWeb satellite constellation|OneWeb constellation]]),<ref name=srb20140603>\n{{cite news |last1=Boucher|first1=Marc |title=Will Google Build a Satellite Constellation? |url=http://spaceref.biz/company/will-google-build-a-satellite-constellation.html |accessdate=25 March 2018 |publisher=SpaceRef Business |date=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj20141107>\n{{cite news |last1=Winkler|first1=Rolfe |last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy |title=Elon Musk\u2019s Next Mission: Internet Satellites  SpaceX, Tesla Founder Explores Venture to Make Lighter, Cheaper Satellites |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-next-mission-internet-satellites-1415390062 |accessdate=25 March 2018 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=11 July 2014}}</ref> \n[[SpaceX]] ([[Starlink]]),<ref name=lat20150116>\n{{cite news |last1=Petersen|first1=Melody |title=Elon Musk and Richard Branson invest in satellite-Internet ventures |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-satellite-entrepreneurs-20150117-story.html |accessdate=19 January 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=16 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=ars20171004>\n{{cite news |last=Brodkin|first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/spacex-and-oneweb-broadband-satellites-raise-fears-about-space-debris/ |title=SpaceX and OneWeb broadband satellites raise fears about space debris |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=2017-10-04 |accessdate=2017-10-07 }}</ref> \n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] ([[Project Kuiper]])<ref name=cnbc20190404>{{cite news |last=Sheetz|first=Michael |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/amazon-project-kuiper-broadband-internet-small-satellite-network.html |title=Amazon wants to launch thousands of satellites so it can offer broadband internet from space |work=[[CNBC]] |date=4 April 2019 |accessdate=19 September 2019 }}</ref><ref name=sn20190708>[https://spacenews.com/amazon-lays-out-constellation-service-goals-deployment-and-deorbit-plans-to-fcc/ Amazon lays out constellation service goals, deployment and deorbit plans to FCC], Caleb Henry, [[SpaceNews]], 8 July 2019, accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> \n[[Samsung]], [[Boeing]], and China (Hongwan),<ref name=satnews20180308/> among others.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Communications satellite constellations|*]]\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access|constellation]]\n[[Category:Spaceflight]]\n\n{{space-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mykhal", "label": "safe", "comment": "punct.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satellite_internet_constellation"}
{"title_page": "1998 German federal election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1998 German federal election\n| country = Germany\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1994 German federal election\n| previous_year = 1994\n| next_election = 2002 German federal election\n| next_year = 2002\n| seats_for_election = All 669 seats in the [[Bundestag]] <br /> 335 seats were needed for a majority\n| election_date      = {{Start date|df=yes|1998|09|27}}\n| registered         = 60,762,751 <small>{{increase}} 0.5%</small>\n| turnout = 49,947,087 (82.2%) <ref name=\"Voter turnout 1998\">{{cite web|title=Voter turnout by election year|url=http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/en/glossar/texte/Wahlbeteiligung.html|website=Website of the Federal Returning Officer's Office|publisher=The Federal Returning Officer|accessdate=7 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107214949/http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/en/glossar/texte/Wahlbeteiligung.html|archivedate=7 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{increase}} 3.2 pp\n\n<!--      SPD   -->\n| image1 = [[File:Gerhardschroeder01.jpg|x160px]]\n| leader1 = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n| party1 = Social Democratic Party of Germany\n| leader_since1 = \u2013\n| last_election1 = 252 seats\n| seats1 = 298\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}46\n| popular_vote1 = 20,181,269\n| percentage1 = 40.9%\n| swing1 = {{increase}}4.5%\n<!--      CDU/CSU  -->\n| image2 = [[File:Helmut Kohl und William S. Cohen (headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader2 = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| party2 = CDU/CSU\n| leader_since2 = 1973\n| last_election2 = 294 seats\n| seats2 = 245\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}49\n| popular_vote2 = 17,329,388\n| percentage2 = 35.1%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}}6.4%\n<!--      Greens   -->\n| image3 = [[File:Fischer und Paul Wolfowitz (Headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader3 =  {{nowrap|[[Joschka Fischer]]}}\n| party3 = Alliance '90/The Greens\n| leader_since3 = \n| last_election3 = 49 seats\n| seats3 = 47\n| seat_change3 = {{decrease}}2\n| popular_vote3 = 3,301,624\n| percentage3 = 6.7%\n| swing3 = {{decrease}}0.6%\n<!--        FDP        -->\n| image4 = [[File:Wolfgang Gerhardt (headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader4 = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]]\n| party4 = Free Democratic Party (Germany)\n| leader_since4 = 1995\n| last_election4 = 47 seats\n| seats4 = 43\n| seat_change4 = {{decrease}}4\n| popular_vote4 = 3,080,955\n| percentage4 = 6.2%\n| swing4 = {{decrease}}0.7%\n<!--        PDS        -->\n| image5 = [[File:Gregor gysi.vortrag 1997.universitaet-hildesheim.jpg|x160px]]\n| leader5 = [[Gregor Gysi]] \n| party5 = Party of Democratic Socialism (Germany)\n| leader_since5 = 1990\n| last_election5 = 30 seats\n| seats5 = 36\n| seat_change5 = {{increase}}6\n| popular_vote5 = 2,515,454\n| percentage5 = 5.1%\n| swing5 = {{increase}}0.7%\n\n<!-- map -->\n| map_image = German Federal Election - Party list vote results by state - 1998.png \n| map_size = 200px \n| map_alt = \n| map = \n| map_caption = [[Party list]] election results by state: red denotes states where the [[SPD]] had the absolute majority of the votes; pink denotes states where the SPD had the plurality of votes; and light blue denotes states where [[CDU/CSU]] had the plurality of votes\n\n<!-- bottom -->\n| title = [[Chancellor of Germany (Federal Republic)|Chancellor]]\n| before_election = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| before_party = CDU/CSU\n| after_election = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n| after_party = Social Democratic Party of Germany\n}}{{Politics of Germany}}\n\n'''Federal elections''' were held in [[Germany]] on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th [[Bundestag]]. The [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]] emerged as the largest faction in parliament, with its leader [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] becoming Chancellor.\n\n== Issues and campaign ==\nSince [[German reunification]] on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.  The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.  Most people blamed the centre-right [[coalition]] government of the [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]]/[[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|Christian Social Union]] (CDU/CSU) and the [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|Free Democratic Party]] (FDP) for the economic difficulties. Longtime Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]]'s government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.\n\nThe 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD questioning who would lead their parties.  There had been rumours that Helmut Kohl would resign and allow [[Wolfgang Sch\u00e4uble]] to take the reins of the CDU but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the [[Chancellor of Germany (Federal Republic)|chancellorship]] for a sixth term. The two contenders for the SPD nomination were [[Oskar Lafontaine]], the party's chairman, and [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]], [[Minister-President]] of [[Lower Saxony]].\n\nOn 1 March 1998, Schr\u00f6der led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.  Schr\u00f6der had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.  In the 1998 general elections, Schr\u00f6der received 47.9 percent.<ref name=\"Pulzer\">Pulzer, Peter. \"The German Federal Election of 1998.\" West European Politics July 1999: 241\u2013249.</ref> Following this election Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schr\u00f6der was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention. For the SPD, Schr\u00f6der offered a new face for the party. He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination. Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.\n\nThe CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl. One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.'  \"Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government.\"<ref name=\"Pulzer\"/> The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.  The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by [[Bill Clinton]] in his [[1992 United States presidential election|successful presidential bid in 1992]].<ref name=\"Green\">Green, Simon. \"The 1998 German Bundestag election: The end of an era.\" Parliamentary Affairs Apr 1999: 52. :Pg. 306\u2013320. LexisNexis Academic. Leslie F. Maplass Library, Macomb, IL. 24 Feb</ref>  The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl but rather focused on their message of a \u201cnew center\".\u2019<ref name=\"Green\"/>\n\nThe FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.  With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had less incentives to vote for the FDP.  The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.  The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.\n\nThe two factions in the Greens, the [[:de:fundi|fundamentalists]] and the [[:de:realo|pragmatists]], had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.\n\nThe major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.  In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's \"limit\" of 4 million unemployed people.  Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.  During the campaign, Schr\u00f6der used this issue against Kohl calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.'  Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.  While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former [[East Germany]] was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent. Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.\n\nAnother issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms. While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled [[Bundesrat of Germany|Bundesrat]] secured the passage of the bill. The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.  While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.  Schr\u00f6der, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue. Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the [[European Union]].\n\n== Results ==\n{{German federal election, 1998}}\n{| style=\"width:70%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ \u2193\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n| style=\"background:red; width:44.5;\" | '''298'''\n| style=\"background:green; width:7.0%;\" | '''47'''\n| style=\"background:black; width:36.6%;\" | '''245'''\n| style=\"background:gold; width:6.4%;\" | '''43'''\n| style=\"background:brown; width:5.4%;\" | '''36'''\n|-\n| <span style=\"color:red;\">'''SPD'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:green;\">'''Gr\u00fcne'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:black;\">'''CDU/CSU'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:gold;\">'''FDP'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:brown;\">'''PDS'''</span>\n|}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Popular Vote\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|'''SPD'''|{{Social Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}}|40.93}}\n{{bar percent|CDU/CSU|{{Christian Democratic Union (Germany)/meta/color}}|35.14}}\n{{bar percent|B'90/GR\u00dcNE|{{Alliance '90/The Greens/meta/color}}|6.70}}\n{{bar percent|FDP|{{Free Democratic Party (Germany)/meta/color}}|6.25}}\n{{bar percent|PDS|#CD1811|5.10}}\n{{bar percent|REP|#0075BE|1.84}}\n{{bar percent|DVU|{{German People's Union/meta/color}}|1.22}}\n{{bar percent|Other|#777777|2.82}}\n}}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Bundestag seats\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|'''SPD'''|{{Social Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}}|44.54}}\n{{bar percent|CDU/CSU|{{Christian Democratic Union (Germany)/meta/color}}|36.62}}\n{{bar percent|B'90/GR\u00dcNE|{{Alliance '90/The Greens/meta/color}}|7.03}}\n{{bar percent|FDP|{{Free Democratic Party (Germany)/meta/color}}|6.43}}\n{{bar percent|PDS|#CD1811|5.38}}\n}}\n\n==Post-election==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Results===\n[[Image:1998 federal german result.svg|thumbnail|320px|Seat results \u2013 SPD in red, Greens in green, PDS in purple, FDP in yellow, CDU/CSU in black]]\n[[Image:Bundestagswahl 1998 Wahlkreisergebnisse.svg|thumbnail|200px|Result by Single-member constituency \u2013 SPD in red, PDS in purple,  CDU/CSU in black]]\nToward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.  Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.  The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag\u2014the first centre-left absolute majority in post-[[World War II]] Germany.  The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from [[1994 German federal election|1994]].\n\nThe CDU/CSU-FDP coalition was severely mauled.  It had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.  The CDU/CSU was particularly hammered; it lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.  Germany's [[mixed member proportional representation|mixed-member proportional]] system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.  It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.  By contrast their junior coalition partner, the FDP, saw their vote hold up well and netted a loss of just 4 seats.\n\nA new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] as chancellor and Greens leader [[Joschka Fischer]] as [[Vice-Chancellor of Germany|vice-chancellor]] and [[Foreign Minister of Germany|foreign minister]].  It was the first [[Red-green alliance|Red-Green coalition]] government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.\n\nHelmut Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman [[Theodor Waigel]].\n\n===Legacy===\n\nThe 1998 German election was historic in many ways.  It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one\u2014the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).\n\nIn addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Helmut Kohl \u2013 the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.  It has been compared to the defeat of [[Winston Churchill]] in [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]] \u2013 both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over. Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the [[Cold War]]).{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* {{Cite book |editor1-last=Conradt |editor1-first=David P. |editor2-last=Kleinfeld |editor2-first=Gerald R. |editor3-last=S\u00f8e |editor3-first=Christian |title=Power Shift in Germany: The 1998 Election and the End of the Kohl Era |publisher=Berghahn Books |year=2000}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* \"Social Democrats win German elections.\" Europe Oct. 1998 [http://www.lexisnexis.com/academic/ LexisNexis Academic]. Leslie F. Maplass Library, Macomb, IL.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041206235227/http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/e/index_e.htm The Federal Returning Officer]\n\n{{German federal elections}}\n\n[[Category:1998 elections in Germany|Federal election]]\n[[Category:Federal elections in Germany|1998]]\n[[Category:September 1998 events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1998 German federal election\n| country = Germany\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1994 German federal election\n| previous_year = 1994\n| next_election = 2002 German federal election\n| next_year = 2002\n| seats_for_election = All 669 seats in the [[Bundestag]] <br /> 335 seats were needed for a majority\n| election_date      = {{Start date|df=yes|1998|09|27}}\n| registered         = 60,762,751 <small>{{increase}} 0.5%</small>\n| turnout = 49,947,087 (82.2%) <ref name=\"Voter turnout 1998\">{{cite web|title=Voter turnout by election year|url=http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/en/glossar/texte/Wahlbeteiligung.html|website=Website of the Federal Returning Officer's Office|publisher=The Federal Returning Officer|accessdate=7 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107214949/http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/en/glossar/texte/Wahlbeteiligung.html|archivedate=7 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{increase}} 3.2 pp\n\n<!--      SPD   -->\n| image1 = [[File:Gerhardschroeder01.jpg|x160px]]\n| leader1 = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n| party1 = Social Democratic Party of Germany\n| leader_since1 = \u2013\n| last_election1 = 252 seats\n| seats1 = 298\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}46\n| popular_vote1 = 20,181,269\n| percentage1 = 40.9%\n| swing1 = {{increase}}4.5%\n<!--      CDU/CSU  -->\n| image2 = [[File:Helmut Kohl und William S. Cohen (headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader2 = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| party2 = CDU/CSU\n| leader_since2 = 1973\n| last_election2 = 294 seats\n| seats2 = 245\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}49\n| popular_vote2 = 17,329,388\n| percentage2 = 35.1%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}}6.4%\n<!--      Greens   -->\n| image3 = [[File:Fischer und Paul Wolfowitz (Headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader3 =  {{nowrap|[[Joschka Fischer]]}}\n| party3 = Alliance '90/The Greens\n| leader_since3 = \n| last_election3 = 49 seats\n| seats3 = 47\n| seat_change3 = {{decrease}}2\n| popular_vote3 = 3,301,624\n| percentage3 = 6.7%\n| swing3 = {{decrease}}0.6%\n<!--        FDP        -->\n| image4 = [[File:Wolfgang Gerhardt (headshot).jpg|x160px]]\n| leader4 = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]]\n| party4 = Free Democratic Party (Germany)\n| leader_since4 = 1995\n| last_election4 = 47 seats\n| seats4 = 43\n| seat_change4 = {{decrease}}4\n| popular_vote4 = 3,080,955\n| percentage4 = 6.2%\n| swing4 = {{decrease}}0.7%\n<!--        PDS        -->\n| image5 = [[File:Gregor gysi.vortrag 1997.universitaet-hildesheim.jpg|x160px]]\n| leader5 = [[Gregor Gysi]] \n| party5 = Party of Democratic Socialism (Germany)\n| leader_since5 = 1990\n| last_election5 = 30 seats\n| seats5 = 36\n| seat_change5 = {{increase}}6\n| popular_vote5 = 2,515,454\n| percentage5 = 5.1%\n| swing5 = {{increase}}0.7%\n\n<!-- map -->\n| map_image = German Federal Election - Party list vote results by state - 1998.png \n| map_size = 200px \n| map_alt = \n| map = \n| map_caption = [[Party list]] election results by state: red denotes states where the [[SPD]] had the absolute majority of the votes; pink denotes states where the SPD had the plurality of votes; and light blue denotes states where [[CDU/CSU]] had the plurality of votes\n\n<!-- bottom -->\n| title = [[Chancellor of Germany (Federal Republic)|Chancellor]]\n| before_election = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| before_party = CDU/CSU\n| after_election = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n| after_party = Social Democratic Party of Germany\n}}{{Politics of Germany}}\n\n'''Federal elections''' were held in [[Germany]] on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th [[Bundestag]]. The [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]] emerged as the largest faction in parliament, with its leader [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] becoming Chancellor.\n\n== Issues and campaign ==\nSince [[German reunification]] on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.  The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.  Most people blamed the centre-right [[coalition]] government of the [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]]/[[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|Christian Social Union]] (CDU/CSU) and the [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|Free Democratic Party]] (FDP) for the economic difficulties. Longtime Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]]'s government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.\n\nThe 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD questioning who would lead their parties.  There had been rumours that Helmut Kohl would resign and allow [[Wolfgang Sch\u00e4uble]] to take the reins of the CDU but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the [[Chancellor of Germany (Federal Republic)|chancellorship]] for a sixth term. The two contenders for the SPD nomination were [[Oskar Lafontaine]], the party's chairman, and [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]], [[Minister-President]] of [[Lower Saxony]].\n\nOn 1 March 1998, Schr\u00f6der led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.  Schr\u00f6der had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.  In the 1998 general elections, Schr\u00f6der received 47.9 percent.<ref name=\"Pulzer\">Pulzer, Peter. \"The German Federal Election of 1998.\" West European Politics July 1999: 241\u2013249.</ref> Following this election Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schr\u00f6der was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention. For the SPD, Schr\u00f6der offered a new face for the party. He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination. Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.\n\nThe CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl. One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.'  \"Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government.\"<ref name=\"Pulzer\"/> The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.  The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by [[Bill Clinton]] in his [[1992 United States presidential election|successful presidential bid in 1992]].<ref name=\"Green\">Green, Simon. \"The 1998 German Bundestag election: The end of an era.\" Parliamentary Affairs Apr 1999: 52. :Pg. 306\u2013320. LexisNexis Academic. Leslie F. Maplass Library, Macomb, IL. 24 Feb</ref>  The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl but rather focused on their message of a \u201cnew center\".\u2019<ref name=\"Green\"/>\n\nThe FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.  With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had less incentives to vote for the FDP.  The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.  The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.\n\nThe two factions in the Greens, the [[:de:fundi|fundamentalists]] and the [[:de:realo|pragmatists]], had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.\n\nThe major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.  In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's \"limit\" of 4 million unemployed people.  Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.  During the campaign, Schr\u00f6der used this issue against Kohl calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.'  Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.  While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former [[East Germany]] was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent. Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.\n\nAnother issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms. While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled [[Bundesrat of Germany|Bundesrat]] secured the passage of the bill. The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.  While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.  Schr\u00f6der, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue. Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the [[European Union]].\n\n== Results ==\n{{German federal election, 1998}}\n{| style=\"width:70%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ \u2193\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n| style=\"background:red; width:44.5;\" | '''298'''\n| style=\"background:green; width:7.0%;\" | '''47'''\n| style=\"background:black; width:36.6%;\" | '''245'''\n| style=\"background:gold; width:6.4%;\" | '''43'''\n| style=\"background:brown; width:5.4%;\" | '''36'''\n|-\n| <span style=\"color:red;\">'''SPD'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:green;\">'''Gr\u00fcne'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:black;\">'''CDU/CSU'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:gold;\">'''FDP'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:brown;\">'''PDS'''</span>\n|}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Popular Vote\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|'''SPD'''|{{Social Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}}|40.93}}\n{{bar percent|CDU/CSU|{{Christian Democratic Union (Germany)/meta/color}}|35.14}}\n{{bar percent|B'90/GR\u00dcNE|{{Alliance '90/The Greens/meta/color}}|6.70}}\n{{bar percent|FDP|{{Free Democratic Party (Germany)/meta/color}}|6.25}}\n{{bar percent|PDS|#CD1811|5.10}}\n{{bar percent|REP|#0075BE|1.84}}\n{{bar percent|DVU|{{German People's Union/meta/color}}|1.22}}\n{{bar percent|Other|#777777|2.82}}\n}}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Bundestag seats\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|'''SPD'''|{{Social Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}}|44.54}}\n{{bar percent|CDU/CSU|{{Christian Democratic Union (Germany)/meta/color}}|36.62}}\n{{bar percent|B'90/GR\u00dcNE|{{Alliance '90/The Greens/meta/color}}|7.03}}\n{{bar percent|FDP|{{Free Democratic Party (Germany)/meta/color}}|6.43}}\n{{bar percent|PDS|#CD1811|5.38}}\n}}\n\n==Post-election==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Results===\n[[Image:1998 federal german result.svg|thumbnail|320px|Seat results \u2013 SPD in red, Greens in green, PDS in purple, FDP in yellow, CDU/CSU in black]]\n[[Image:Bundestagswahl 1998 Wahlkreisergebnisse.svg|thumbnail|200px|Result by Single-member constituancy \u2013 SPD in red, PDS in purple,  CDU/CSU in black]]\nToward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.  Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.  The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag\u2014the first centre-left absolute majority in post-[[World War II]] Germany.  The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from [[1994 German federal election|1994]].\n\nThe CDU/CSU-FDP coalition was severely mauled.  It had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.  The CDU/CSU was particularly hammered; it lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.  Germany's [[mixed member proportional representation|mixed-member proportional]] system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.  It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.  By contrast their junior coalition partner, the FDP, saw their vote hold up well and netted a loss of just 4 seats.\n\nA new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] as chancellor and Greens leader [[Joschka Fischer]] as [[Vice-Chancellor of Germany|vice-chancellor]] and [[Foreign Minister of Germany|foreign minister]].  It was the first [[Red-green alliance|Red-Green coalition]] government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.\n\nHelmut Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman [[Theodor Waigel]].\n\n===Legacy===\n\nThe 1998 German election was historic in many ways.  It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one\u2014the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).\n\nIn addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Helmut Kohl \u2013 the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.  It has been compared to the defeat of [[Winston Churchill]] in [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]] \u2013 both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over. Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the [[Cold War]]).{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* {{Cite book |editor1-last=Conradt |editor1-first=David P. |editor2-last=Kleinfeld |editor2-first=Gerald R. |editor3-last=S\u00f8e |editor3-first=Christian |title=Power Shift in Germany: The 1998 Election and the End of the Kohl Era |publisher=Berghahn Books |year=2000}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* \"Social Democrats win German elections.\" Europe Oct. 1998 [http://www.lexisnexis.com/academic/ LexisNexis Academic]. Leslie F. Maplass Library, Macomb, IL.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041206235227/http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/e/index_e.htm The Federal Returning Officer]\n\n{{German federal elections}}\n\n[[Category:1998 elections in Germany|Federal election]]\n[[Category:Federal elections in Germany|1998]]\n[[Category:September 1998 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResults:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: constituancy \u2192 constituency", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_German_federal_election"}
